content.description: Start 5 feet left of a crack that leads to a shallow chimmeny.   The devils lake guide book says start 5 feet left of route 11.   Climb face to first ledge then from there move left and center to straight up.
content.protection: 2 Trees at top for top rope anchors
content.location: Hole in the wall 15 to the right of the hole if looking at the wall.

content.description: Maybe a touch too high to boulder this? Go ahead and find out, I just TR'd it. Fun moves.
content.location: Just right of "Hole" climb to the level of the hole and then go up slightly right.

content.description: Nice start in a very shallow right-facing corner.  Above is some nice stemming.
content.protection: Two good, finger-sized pieces low.  Shallow, flared, tiny wires and ball nuts up high.
content.location: 25-30 feet uphill from the Hole, beside the big oak tree.

content.description:
Great route! Thin Crack and flake system. Once to flake move slightly right and then straight up. 

  Flake is located in a Dark watermark.
content.location: If looking at the hole in the wall Left arm is 10 feet to the right in a dark wateramrk.

content.description: More of a highball boulder problem this climbs some fun moves on good gear to the "hole" and straight up.
content.location: Left side of crag, find the "hole" and climb straight up to it and straight to the top.

content.description:
Start in awkward crack with a couple moves to the shallow chimney, not worth the trek out here but if you're here anyway...   

  #11 p172 Swartling
content.location: To the right of White Cloud, the furthest right climb on the main wall.

content.description: On the left side of the wall. Start on jugs. Climb up the the vertical slashes on the clean face. From a prominentÂ triangle slot make a big move up and left to a jug to easier climbing above.
content.protection: Boulder pads or a top rope. Doesn't look like there is good gear if you were to lead it.
content.location: Directly below the boulder problem Bulbous by 150 feet, or right above the boulder problem Battlewound (easiest way).

content.description: Climb the gently overhanging finger crack just left of a large pine tree.  As the name suggests, it is possible to bail from this route by leaning back onto this tree, though this is fairly easily avoided while actually climbing.  Avoid reaching out left to the large flake system.  Complete the climb with a kind of scary mantle (pro beneath your feet with the tree waiting right behind you).
content.location: Finger crack left and around the corner from Hole in the Wall.  Start on the left side of a large, solid, flake and go straight up.  I moved a bit right to finish at the end after the crack runs out.

content.description: #12 p172 from Swartling.  Not super memorable, but easily protectable and a couple committing moves on this one.
content.location: Left side of the wall on the right at "Hole In The Wall".  Huge tree on top for an anchor.

content.description: A bit heady for 5.5, and protection isn't quite as good as you might wish, but it's all there.  #13 p172 Swartling
content.location: Right side of the small wall to the right of "Hole In The Wall".

content.description: Short wall with a few interesting climbs.
